    <section id="Feel">
        <br>
        <br>
        <h2>Starting of Dhamma</h2>
        <p>After the Kalinga war now Odisha after the Kalinga war he saw that around 100,000 kalinga civilians died and more than 10,000 of Ashoka's own warriors died in this war,there so many people died that the river Daya truned red. He felt very bad that he decided to do Ahinsa or non-voilence after that he stopped the expansion of his Empire and got a title of "Ashoka the great".</p>
    </section>
    <section id="ed">
        <br>
        <br>
        <h5>Edicts</h5>
        <p>Edicts were writings that were written on rocks,pillars etc. This help people to spread dhamma.</p>
        <p>There are four major types of edicts made by Ashoka</p>
        <p>Minor Rock Edicts</p>
        <p>Minor Pillar Edicts</p>
        <p>Major Rock Edicts</p>
        <p>Major Pillar Edicts</p><hr>
        <p>There were total 33 edicts they were found inthe areas of modern-day Afghanistan, Bangladesh, India, Nepal, and Pakistan and most were written in Brahmi Script</p>
    </section>
    <section id="solve">
        <br>
        <br>
        <h3>Spread of Dhamma</h3>
        <p>1. He appointed officials who were called Dhamma Mahamatta who went place to place teaching people about Dhamma</p>
        <p>2. Ashoka got his messages inscribed on rocks and pillars instructing his officals to read his message who can not able to read.</p>
        <p>3. He also built roads, wellan rest houses for people.</p>
        <p>4. He arranged medical facilities for human and animal both.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="me">
        <br>
        <br>
        <h4>Message of Ashoka</h4>
        <p>His message was just simple that when a new child is born or something great happens with us and when someone get ill they do many things and sacrificesand these rituals we do are not useful to us in anyway. He told that we should gentle with everyone even with slaves, servants and he told to respect eachothers religion and he was buddha but he never told to follow his religion.</p>
    </section>
